---------------------------------------------------------------------
APPENDIX : How to apply this license to your work
---------------------------------------------------------------------

To apply the Public Attribution License (PAL) to your work, attach the
following notice, replacing [year], [name of author(s)], and either
your name(s), pseudonym(s), or 'Anonymous' as appropriate. Include the
full text of this license.

Example notice for a work by one or more named authors:

  Copyright (C) [year] [name(s) of author(s)]

  This work is licensed under the Public Attribution License (PAL).
  You may do whatever you want with it, subject to attribution of the
  author(s) as [name(s) of author(s)], the no‑liability terms, and the
  notice‑preservation terms. The complete license text is included below.

Example notice for an anonymous work:

  Copyright (C) [year] Anonymous

  This work is licensed under the Public Attribution License (PAL).
  You may do whatever you want with it, subject to attribution of the
  work as by 'Anonymous', the no‑liability terms, and the
  notice‑preservation terms. The complete license text is included below.

Place the notice in a prominent location (e.g., file header, README,
description field, or accompanying text file). No further restrictions
apply beyond attribution, notice preservation, and disclaimer of
liability.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
SUBSECTIONS FOR SPECIFIC CONTENT TYPES
---------------------------------------------------------------------

A. For images (photographs, illustrations, graphics, memes, etc.):

   Embed the license notice in the image metadata (EXIF, IPTC, XMP) if
   possible. If not, accompany the image with a plain text file named
   "LICENSE.txt" or "PAL_NOTICE.txt" containing the copyright year,
   author name(s) (or 'Anonymous'), and the statement: "Licensed under
   the Public Attribution License (PAL) – see attached license text."
   For online distribution, include the notice in the image's alt text
   or a visible caption.

B. For video (films, clips, animations, streaming content):

   Include the license notice in the video credits or a dedicated title
   card for at least 3 seconds. Additionally, embed the notice in the
   video's metadata container (e.g., MOV, MKV, or MP4 tags). For
   platform-based uploads (YouTube, Vimeo, etc.), place the notice in
   the video description field, and if possible, as a pinned comment or
   end screen.

   **Opening screen excerpt (display as a title card or disclaimer):**

   Place the following text on a plain or semi‑transparent background
   for at least 3 seconds near the beginning of the video, before main
   content begins. You may reformat the layout (centered, smaller font,
   with or without a border) as long as the words remain legible.

   --- BEGIN EXCERPT ---

   This work is licensed under the
   Public Attribution License (PAL).

   Author: [name(s) or 'Anonymous' as specified by the Licensor]

   You may do whatever you want with this video,
   subject to attribution, notice preservation,
   and the no‑liability terms.

   Full license text is included with this video
   or available at [ https://github.com/druvx13/PAL/blob/main/LICENSE ].

   --- END EXCERPT ---

   If the author chooses anonymity, replace the author line with:
   "Author: Anonymous"

   You may shorten the excerpt further for very short clips (e.g.,
   under 10 seconds) to only:

   "PAL licensed – see description for terms. Author: [name/Anonymous]"

   However, the full opening screen (above) is recommended for
   standalone videos.

C. For text (blog posts, articles, documentation, books, code snippets):

   For short works (e.g., blog posts, articles), include the notice at
   the beginning or end of the document. For longer works (books,
   manuals), place the notice on a copyright page or in a dedicated
   section. For code snippets, include the notice as a comment block at
   the top of each file, or in a root LICENSE file for a repository.

D. For any other content type (audio, 3D models, datasets, presentations):

   Follow the same principle: attach the notice in a location visible
   to a reasonable user or embedded in the file's standard metadata
   fields. If no metadata exists, provide a companion text file named
   "PAL_LICENSE.txt" alongside the content.
